<subSubSection id="C31665703230FFC583B9F9002820FE4E" lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="17" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BB336FB3230FFC583B9F9002E0FFE86" blockId="15.[151,1437,1699,2013]" lastBlockId="16.[151,1437,150,393]" lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="17" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
A new karyotype for the genus was described by 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9D4B0A3230FFDA8187F9002FE1F926" author="Silva, M. J. J. &amp; Percequillo, A. R. &amp; Yonenaga-Yassuda, Y." box="[761,970,1735,1761]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="219 - 226" refId="ref73592" refString="Silva, M. J. J., Percequillo, A. R. &amp; Yonenaga-Yassuda, Y. (2000) Cytogenetics and systematic approach on a new Oryzomys species, of the nitidus group (Sigmodontinae, Rodentia) from Northeastern Brazil. Caryologia, 53, 219 - 226. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00087114.2000.10589199" type="journal article" year="2000">
Silva 
<emphasis id="B978EAE93230FFDA8045F9002F46F926" box="[827,877,1735,1761]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">et al</emphasis>
. (2000)
</bibRefCitation>
. Karyotype: 2n = 76 and FN = 86. Autosomal complement: six metacentric pairs (two large and four small), and 31 acrocentric pairs decreasing in size from large to small. Sex chromosomes: X, a large subtelocentric; Y chromosome presented two different morphologies, a medium submetacentric (Ya), and a medium acrocentric (Yb). C-banding metaphases exhibited blocks of constitutive heterochromatin on the pericentromeric region of all autosomes. The short arm of X and the entirely Y chromosome were heterochromatic. G-banding was also performed. Multiple NORs, varying from four to nine were localized at the telomeric regions of the short arms of small acrocentric chromosomes. FISH with telomeric sequences revealed signals exclusively at the ends of all chromosome arms and no interstitial signals were observed (
<bibRefCitation id="EF9D4B0A322FFFC583E1FF502D75FF76" author="Silva, M. J. J. &amp; Percequillo, A. R. &amp; Yonenaga-Yassuda, Y." box="[159,350,151,177]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" pagination="219 - 226" refId="ref73592" refString="Silva, M. J. J., Percequillo, A. R. &amp; Yonenaga-Yassuda, Y. (2000) Cytogenetics and systematic approach on a new Oryzomys species, of the nitidus group (Sigmodontinae, Rodentia) from Northeastern Brazil. Caryologia, 53, 219 - 226. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00087114.2000.10589199" type="journal article" year="2000">
Silva 
<emphasis id="B978EAE9322FFFC5839CFF502D3FFF76" box="[226,276,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">et al</emphasis>
. 2000
</bibRefCitation>
, pp. 220, 
<figureCitation id="13372A7E322FFFC582B1FF502E3BFF76" box="[463,528,151,177]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1976,2000]" captionTargetBox="[165,1422,1069,1943]" captionTargetId="figure-342@4.[159,1429,1062,1950]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Collection localities of Oryzomyini species analyzed in this work. (1) Claúdia, Mato Grosso state; (2) and (3) Rio Japurá, Amazonas state; (4) and (5) Rio Içá, Amazonas state." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4423617" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4423617/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). According to the authors, the karyotype of 
<taxonomicName id="4C0C4D78322FFFC5876CFF502890FF76" baseAuthorityName="Thomas" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[1042,1211,151,177]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Euryoryzomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macconnelli">
<emphasis id="B978EAE9322FFFC5876CFF502890FF76" box="[1042,1211,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">E. macconnelli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(2n = 76, FN = 85) from 
<collectingCountry id="F31B766B322FFFC583AAFF7C2D6CFF12" box="[212,327,187,213]" name="Venezuela" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EF9D4B0A322FFFC5822BFF7C2E03FF12" author="Musser, G. G. &amp; Carleton, M. D. &amp; Brothers, E. M. &amp; Gardner, A. L." box="[341,552,187,213]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" pagination="1 - 376" refId="ref69760" refString="Musser, G. G., Carleton, M. D., Brothers, E. M. &amp; Gardner, A. L. (1998) Systematic studies of Oryzomyine rodents (Muridae, Sigmodontinae): diagnoses and distributions of species formerly assigned to Oryzomys &quot; capito &quot;. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 236, 1 - 376." type="journal article" year="1998">
Musser 
<emphasis id="B978EAE9322FFFC582CEFF7C2DCAFF12" box="[432,481,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">et al</emphasis>
. 1998
</bibRefCitation>
) was different from 
<taxonomicName id="4C0C4D78322FFFC58073FF7C2F86FF13" authority="Moreira &amp; Ventura &amp; Percequillo &amp; Yonenaga-Yassuda, 2020" authorityName="Moreira &amp; Ventura &amp; Percequillo &amp; Yonenaga-Yassuda" authorityYear="2020" box="[781,941,187,212]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Euryoryzomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B978EAE9322FFFC58073FF7C2F86FF13" box="[781,941,187,212]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Euryoryzomys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A24B5792322FFFC580CAFF7C2826FF12" box="[948,1037,187,213]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, because in the former there was no large metacentric chromosomes, and there was five metacentric small pairs while in the latter karyotype, two large metacentrics was observed as well as four small metacentric pairs. Sex chromosomes was also distinctive between both karyotypes (
<bibRefCitation id="EF9D4B0A322FFFC58224FEE02E33FE86" author="Silva, M. J. J. &amp; Percequillo, A. R. &amp; Yonenaga-Yassuda, Y." box="[346,536,295,321]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" pagination="219 - 226" refId="ref73592" refString="Silva, M. J. J., Percequillo, A. R. &amp; Yonenaga-Yassuda, Y. (2000) Cytogenetics and systematic approach on a new Oryzomys species, of the nitidus group (Sigmodontinae, Rodentia) from Northeastern Brazil. Caryologia, 53, 219 - 226. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00087114.2000.10589199" type="journal article" year="2000">
Silva 
<emphasis id="B978EAE9322FFFC582E2FEE02DE6FE86" box="[412,461,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">et al</emphasis>
. 2000
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB336FB322FFFC583B9FE8C2820FE4E" blockId="16.[151,1437,150,393]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
We present a different karyotype for the genus, here referred as 
<taxonomicName id="4C0C4D78322FFFC580F4FE8C2801FEA3" authorityName="Moreira &amp; Ventura &amp; Percequillo &amp; Yonenaga-Yassuda" authorityYear="2020" box="[906,1066,331,356]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Euryoryzomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B978EAE9322FFFC580F4FE8C2801FEA3" box="[906,1066,331,356]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Euryoryzomys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. The cytogenetic analysis was performed for three males collected in Rio Japurá, Amazonas, 
<collectingCountry id="F31B766B322FFFC5802AFEA82FB3FE4E" box="[852,920,367,393]" name="Brazil" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<tableCitation id="C68E0340322FFFC580D9FEA82FD1FE4E" box="[935,1018,367,393]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="5.[151,239,151,175]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="TABLE 1. Species, field and laboratory number, sex, diploid (2n) and fundamental (FN) numbers and collection localities of Oryzomyini species studied in this work." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF736673323AFFD083E9FF502E41FF14" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" tableUuid="DF736673323AFFD083E9FF502E41FF14">Table 1</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
